4 A JOINT RESOLUTION OF THE SENATE AND THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE STATE OF
5 MONTANA SUPPORTING THE PROTECTION AND RETENTION OF NATIONAL PUBLIC LANDS.
6
7 WHEREAS, Montanans have a deep love and affection for our shared national public lands and the
8 innumerable benefits they provide; and
9 WHEREAS, Montana and the American West contain a variety of national public lands, including
10 national parks, national forests, wildlife refuges, national monuments, wilderness areas, and other public lands;
11 and
12 WHEREAS, Montanans' affection for public lands extends to protected areas from the Going-to-the-
13 Sun Road in Glacier National Park to the Capitol Rock Natural Landmark in the Custer Gallatin National Forest
14 and all of the acres of public lands in between managed by federal agencies that feature iconic working
15 ranches, mountain bike trail systems, world-class climbing, outstanding whitewater rafting, historical centers,
16 museums, and incredible hunting and angling opportunities; and
17 WHEREAS, our public lands reflect many of our most noble democratic ideals because public lands
18 offer valuable recreational, economic, cultural, and spiritual opportunities for everyone, regardless of one's
19 socioeconomic status, race, or gender or whether one lives in an urban or rural area; and
20 WHEREAS, our public lands provide defining features of Montana and the foundation for our quality of
21 life by supporting the vitality of our communities, as well as representing Montana's common heritage.
22 WHEREAS, our national public lands in Montana feature an amazingly diverse range of landscapes,
23 from the snowcapped peaks of the Rocky Mountains down to rushing rivers, from canyons to sagebrush seas,
24 and the tree-lined mountain valleys that are treasured by Montanans for outdoor recreation, such as hunting,
25 angling, downhill and cross country skiing, and snowmobiling; and
26 WHEREAS, our public lands provide important wildlife habitats, clean water, clean air, and natural
27 amenities that contribute to Montanans' quality of life and Montana's climate resiliency; and
28 WHEREAS, according to the 2024 Voter Survey on Public Lands conducted by the University of
