1 Montana, 95% of Montanans visited national public lands in the previous year, 83% believe national public
2 lands help the state economy, and 82% want presidents to continue protecting national public lands by
3 designating them as national monuments; and
4 WHEREAS, our shared public lands have a substantial impact on economic development and jobs
5 through mineral extraction, timber sales, ranching, grazing, and the outdoor recreation and tourism industry,
6 which alone accounted for over $5.8 billion dollars spent in the state in 2022 and 2023 by nonresidents; and
7 WHEREAS, misguided attempts to seize control of vast acreage of national public lands from the
8 American public and to force their disposal through litigation and legislation, supported by a multimillion-dollar
9 ad campaign, are inconsistent with the values and interests of Montanans; and
10 WHEREAS, public land managers, federal funding, and federal staffing are integral to the protection of
11 public lands so they may be enjoyed by Montanans.
12
13 NOW, THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE AND THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF
14 THE STATE OF MONTANA:
15 That the 69th Legislature of the State of Montana:
16 (1) supports keeping our national public lands in public hands through the stewardship of the
17 United States government and the federal land management agencies dedicated to their protection and access;
18 (2) opposes efforts to sell, transfer, or dispose of either our national public lands or state public
19 lands; and
20 (3) encourages Montana's Governor, Attorney General, and the members of Montana's
21 Congressional Delegation to take actions THAT may be necessary to oppose future attempts to sell, transfer, or
22 dispose of our national public lands to either private buyers or the states themselves.
23 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that the Secretary of State send a copy of this RESOLUTION to Governor
24 Greg Gianforte, the Montana Congressional Delegation, Secretary of the Interior Doug Burgum, and President
25 Donald J. Trump.
